bidding last year.

00:34:14.440 --> 00:34:16.550
The idea here is quite simple.

00:34:16.550 --> 00:34:20.170
We let all the networks
that participate bid

00:34:20.170 --> 00:34:26.139
in to a single auction in real
time, and the winner wins.

00:34:26.139 --> 00:34:27.219
It's that simple.

00:34:27.219 --> 00:34:29.290
So unlike traditional
mediation, which

00:34:29.290 --> 00:34:31.690
is how a lot of the
industry works today,

00:34:31.690 --> 00:34:35.170
instead of having to take
average historical data

00:34:35.170 --> 00:34:39.429
and then use that to prioritize
a bunch of different networks

00:34:39.429 --> 00:34:42.850
and then call them in
sequence, so instead

00:34:42.850 --> 00:34:44.512
of having to work
through all that,

00:34:44.512 --> 00:34:46.179
we're taking all the
networks, and we're

00:34:46.179 --> 00:34:47.949
calling them at one time.

00:34:47.949 --> 00:34:50.350
You get the bids,
and they compete

00:34:50.350 --> 00:34:54.929
in a single, unified auction.

00:34:54.929 --> 00:34:57.200
So that means for
any given impression,

00:34:57.200 --> 00:35:01.570
whoever is willing to
pay the highest wins.

00:35:01.570 --> 00:35:02.290
That's it.

00:35:02.290 --> 00:35:04.210
Because all these
networks are competing

00:35:04.210 --> 00:35:08.270
at exactly the same level,
the same time, same priority,

00:35:08.270 --> 00:35:08.830
even Google.

00:35:11.790 --> 00:35:13.200
